== Usage ==
{{nihongo|'''[[:en:Ruby character|Ruby character]]s'''|ルビ|Rubi}} are small, annotative [[gloss (annotation)|gloss]]es that can be placed above or to the right of a [[:en:Chinese character|Chinese character]] when writing languages with [[logogram|logographic]] characters such as [[:en:Chinese language|Chinese]] or [[:en:Japanese language|Japanese]] to show the pronunciation. Typically called just '''ruby''' or '''rubi''', such annotations are used as pronunciation guides for characters that are likely to be unfamiliar to the reader.

* {{tlx|Ruby|人|rén}} → {{Ruby|人|rén}}
* {{tlx|Ruby|人|ひと}} → {{Ruby|人|ひと}}
* {{tlx|Ruby|人|인}} → {{Ruby|人|인}}

The first parameter is the base (the lower part) and the second is the Ruby text (the smaller part on top or in parentheses).

* {{para|large|yes}} enlarges the characters by 250% for use in examples

Examples:

{{markup
|<nowiki>{{Ruby|全|すべ}}て</nowiki>
|{{Ruby|全|すべ}}て

|<nowiki>{{Ruby|媽|mā}}</nowiki>
|{{Ruby|媽|mā}}

|<nowiki>{{Ruby|large=yes|媽|mā}}</nowiki>
|{{Ruby|large=yes|媽|mā}}
}}

== Browser support ==
The manner in which the Ruby characters are displayed is dependent upon the browser. For browser support, see [https://caniuse.com/ruby Ruby annotation] at ''Can I use''.

For example: {{Ruby|Base|top}}

If you see {{overset|top|Base}}, then your browser supports Ruby.

If you see Base (top), then your browser does not support Ruby.

== See also ==
* {{tl|ruby line}} for easier annotation of multiple series of characters
* {{tl|ruby-zh-p}} for [[:en:Hanyu Pinyin|Hanyu Pinyin]]
* {{tl|ruby-zh-b}} for [[:en:Bopomofo|Bopomofo]]
* {{tl|ruby-ja}} for Japanese
* {{tl|Linked Ruby}} for easier wikilinks to Ruby annotations
* {{tl|overset}} for oversetting characters for math and similar uses

